though we necessarily look on his times as past, of course experienced them as present. His times were times of crisis. Scott, then, has much to share in the experience, narration, anticipation and response to change as a condition of life – a condition our era, with its existential challenges to climate, to public health, to civilization knows only too well. In Scott at 250, major scholars foreground the author as theorist of tomorrow – as the surveyor of the complexities of the present who also gazes, as we do, toward an anxious and hopeful future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aChange in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aDuncan, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerris, Ina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFielding, Penny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJarrells, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangan, Celeste, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLumsden, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCracken-Flesher, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOliver, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrice, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWickman, Matthew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWickman, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311078040640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147442988740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474429887423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.